Task¶

Simple Scatterplot Matrix¶

Select a couple of numerical attributes (e.g., those of 2017) and create a scatterplot matrix (e.g., with pandas or seaborn).

In [14]:
pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(df[['games12','minutes12','assists12', 'games13','minutes13','assists13']], 
                           figsize=(20,20), 
                           alpha=0.7, 
                           color='tab:green', 
                           s=100
                          );

Colored Scatterplot Matrix¶

Select a categorical attribute and encode its values with color in the scatterplot matrix. See: seaborn pairplot.

In [15]:
g = sns.pairplot(df.dropna(), 
                 vars = ['games12','minutes12','assists12', 'games13','minutes13','assists13'], 
                 hue="position",
                 palette="husl",
                 markers=["o", "D"],
                 plot_kws=dict(s=50, edgecolor="y", linewidth=1),
                 )
In [9]:
g = sns.pairplot(df.dropna(), 
                 vars = ['games12','minutes12','assists12', 'games13','minutes13','assists13'], 
                 hue="foot",
                 palette="husl",
                 markers=["o", "D",'s'],
                 plot_kws=dict(s=50, edgecolor="y", linewidth=1))

Interpretation¶

Scatterplot matrix generally shows relation ships between all attributes selected and also spread of all attributes as well.

We have selected attributes ['games12','minutes12','assists12', 'games13','minutes13','assists13'] to see the relationship between attributes. Diaginal generally shows spread of that attribute. Each other cell shows relationship between those two attributes who intersect there.

We can see from graphs that columns having games data and playtime has linear relationship which shows that one attribute increases with value of another attribute. Notice cell where games12 and minutes12 & games13 and minutes13 intersect.

We can notice that there is not particular relationship between 2 games. We can notice somewhat linear relationship between games and assists data though but its not as strong as between games and minutes.

We also have color coded based on categorical variable position in one graph and foot in another graph to differentiate points but it seems they are kind of overlaping.

The scatterplot matrices show the obvious relationships, like that the total playtime (minutes17) increases with the number of games a player attended, or that players who score the most goals also play most often.

The additional color coding in the scatterplot matrix reveals a a small difference in the number of goals scored between the positions.
